She asked the director of the Museum of Modern Art, a particular offender in gender exclusiveness, about women abstract painters. He reeled off a whole list of names of women artists, of whom some were much better than their male colleagues. None the less, he did not collect their work. Peggy Guggenheim decided to show them. Many women agreed. Some did not. There was a risk. Being shown only with women might endorse the gender divide. Decide not to show and you might remain marginal and invisible. Lee Krasner risked it; Georgia O’Keeffe refused.
